    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>To End the Conflict in Africa</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>P P Lakshman letter on Makau Mutua's Aug 30 article backs calls for partition of Tutsi and Hutu in Rwanda and Burundi</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I hope the case made by Makau Mutua (''The Tutsi and Hutu Need a Partition,'' Op-Ed, Aug. 30) will get the attention of all concerned. I speak from the personal experience and anguish of India's independence movement and the partition of the Indian subcontinent half a century ago.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I hope the case made by Makau Mutua (''The Tutsi and Hutu Need a Partition,'' Op-Ed, Aug. 30) will get the attention of all concerned. I speak from the personal experience and anguish of India's independence movement and the partition of the Indian subcontinent half a century ago.</p>
        <p>Partition in central Africa may appear unthinkable, as was the case in the Indian subcontinent even 10 years before it actually happened in 1947. But boundaries are not sacrosanct for all time. It requires statesmanship and willingness to learn from history's lessons and think the unthinkable, not only in Europe but in Asia and Africa as well.</p>
        <p>President Clinton has expressed remorse for not taking any action when genocide was taking place in Africa. He could help in preventing it from happening again.</p>
        <p>P. P. LAKSHMAN  New York, Aug. 31, 2000</p>
      </block>
